Received 00th January 20xx, Accepted 00th January 20xx The  symbiotic  relationships  between  actinobacteria  and  eukaryotic  organisms  are  found  everywhere  and  may  even  shape  entire  ecosystems.1  In  recent  decades,  it  has  been  demonstrated  that  symbiotic  microorganisms  have  the  ability  to  biosynthesize  secondary  metabolites  with  high  biological  potential.2-3  These  compounds  are  a  response  to  the  different  environmental  pressures  to  which  the  organisms  are  exposed,  playing  a  vital  function in chemical ecology, and acting mainly as defenders of the  nutritional  resources  of  their  hosts  against  predators,  parasites,  pathogenic or competing microorganisms.3-4 In social insects, most  symbionts  act  by  several  mechanisms,  such  as  nutritional  source,  chemical  defense  and  communication.3,5  Beneficial  microbial  associations may augment integral immune defenses helping in the  control  of  diseases  and  parasites  via  microbial  competition,  by  stimulating  secretion  of  antimicrobial compounds.6 More than 500 species of stingless bees (Hymenoptera, Apidae,  Meliponini) have been described, making them the largest group of  a.Departamento  de  Ciências  Farmacêuticas,  Faculdade  de  Ciências  Farmacêuticas  de Ribeirão Preto, Universidade de São Paulo, 14040-903 Ribeirão Preto, SP, Brazil     E-mail: mtpupo@fcfrp.usp.br b.Departamento  de  Biologia,  Faculdade  de  Filosofia,  Ciências  e  Letras  de  Ribeirão  Electronic  Supplementary  supplementary  DOI: 10.1039/x0xx00000x Preto, Universidade de São Paulo, 14040-901 Ribeirão Preto, SP, Brazil Actinobacteria associated with stingless bee biosynthesize bioactive  polyketides against bacterial pathogen

Diego  Rodríguez-Hernándeza,  Weilan  G.  P.  Meloa,  Carla  Menegattia,  Vitor  B.  Lourenzona,  Fábio S. do Nascimentob, Mônica T. Pupo*a.  Social insects can establish nutritional, communication and defensive symbiotic associations with microorganisms, among  which  actinobacteria  that  play  important  roles  in  these  symbioses.  Stingless  bees  are  characterized  by  keeping  their  colonies  free  of  diseases  and  parasites.  These  bees  have  evolved  different  protective  strategies,  but  most  are  still  unknown.  Here  we  explore  the  potential  of  the  stingless  bee  Mellipona  scutellaris  to  associate  with  actinobacteria  to  suppress  pathogenic  microbes.  Seven  actinobacteria  strains  were  isolated  from  foraging  and  nurse  bees  and  identified  through  16S  rRNA  sequencing.  Tree  of  these  strains  exhibited  pronounced  growth  inhibition  against  the  specialized  pathogen  of  honey  bees  Paenibacillus  larvae,  the  causative  agent  of  American  Foulbrood.  Bioassay-guided  HPLC  fractionation, followed by NMR and mass spectrometry-based structure elucidation, revealed the presence of lobophorins  (1-4)  and  anthracyclines  (5-15)  families  isolated  from  the  strains  Streptomyces  sp.  ICBG1323  and  Micromonospora  sp.  ICBG1321, all responsible for this activity. The  stingless  bee  Melipona  scutellaris  (Hymenoptera,  Apidae,  Meliponini), an endemic species from the northeastern of Brazil, is  popularly known as "uruçu", or "uruçu verdadeira".20 This stingless  bee  plays  an  is  characterized  to  produce  high  quality  honey.20  However,  human  activity has reduced the populations of M. scutellaris. It is necessary  to deepen the study of this species for its conservation.21 Recently,  we  described  a  protective  association  between  the  bacterium  Paenibacillus polymyxa ALLI-03-01 and M. scutellaris. This bacterial  strain  isolated  from  the  larval  food  produced  (L)-(−)-3-phenyllactic  acid  and  fusaricidins,  which  showed  antimicrobial  activity  against  the specialized pathogen of honey bees Paenibacillus larvae and the  general entomopathogenic fungus Beauveria bassiana.22 As part of an ongoing ICBG-Brazil project,23 we pursued studies  in  the  search  of  secondary  metabolites  from  actinobacteria  associated  with  Melipona  scutellaris  bees  that  could  act  as  defensive  compounds  against  the  entomopathogenic  bacterium  P.  larvae.  We  have  used  actinobacteria-specific  culture  methods  for  isolation,  16S  rRNA  gene  sequencing  for  bacterial  microbial  identification,  growth  inhibition  assays  for  antimicrobial  activity,  analytical chemistry techniques for isolation of compounds, and MS  and  NMR  analyses  for  structural  analyses,  which  led  to  the  identification  of  two  families  of  bioactive  compounds,  known  as  lobophorins (1-4) and anthracyclines (5-15), from Streptomyces sp.  ICBG1323 and Micromonospora sp. ICBG1321, respectively.

The  isolation  of  actinobacteria  resulted  in  seven  strains  from  nurse  and  foraging  bees.  The  most  common  morphologies  found  were defined by color of culture, including gray, white, brown, and  red  (see  Figure  S1  in  the  supplementary  material).  The  16S  rRNA  sequencing  showed  that  six  isolated  actinobacteria  belong  to  Streptomyces  genus,  while  one  Micromonospora  strain  was  identified  (Figure  S1,  Table  S1  in  the  supplementary  material).  Streptomyces  sp.  ICBG1323  and  Streptomyces  sp.  ICBG1324  were  isolated  from  foraging  bees,  while  the  other  strains  Streptomyces  sp.  ICBG1318,  Streptomyces  sp.  ICBG1313,  Streptomyces  sp.  ICBG1307  and  Micromonospora  sp.   ICBG1321 were isolated from nurse bees.  in  pairwise  interactions  against  fungi,  Beauveria  bassiana  and  Metarhizium  anisopliae,  and  the  bacteria  Paenibacillus  larvae,  the  causative  agent  of  American  Foulbrood  disease of honeybees (see Table S2 in the supplementary material). ICBG1323  are  spirotetronate  macrolides,  and  belong  to  a  family  of  polyketides  characterized  by  spirocyclic  tetronate  moiety  conjugated  with  a  trans-decalin  moiety  by  carbonyl unit, decorated by various deoxy oligosaccharides.27 Their  biosynthesis is through a linear carbon skeleton that is catalyzed by  a PKS-I module, followed by a [4 + 2] cycloaddition generating the  macrocycle framework. Subsequent hydroxylation and glycosylation  at  different  aglycone  positions  lead  to  significant  structural  diversity.28 All natural spirotetronates described in the literature to  date have been obtained from actinobacteria. Typical structures of  the  spirotetronate  group  include  tetrocarcin  A,  chlorothricin,  and  kijanimicin.28

The  glycosylate  quinocycline  kosinostatin  (14)  and  its  stereoisomer  isoquinocycline B (15) were the most potent compounds, with MIC  =  40  nM  and  190  nM,  respectively.
